    {
        "content": "<p>hello everyone, I'm new here. I was looking for a CT themed chat because I couldn't find the answer to a question online. What is it called when in a category, you take an object and all the objects and morphisms that are reachable from it? I'd call it the closure of that object but apparently that's not what it's called.</p>",
        "id": 252605848,
        "sender_full_name": "Péter Ferenczy",
        "timestamp": 1631184944
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You might call it the connected component, if you ignore the direction of arrows.</p>",
        "id": 252607298,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1631185741
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>interesting, although I am looking for the directed reachable subcategory (it does form a category, because all identities and compositions are preserved). maybe could be called the forward connected component?</p>",
        "id": 252607566,
        "sender_full_name": "Péter Ferenczy",
        "timestamp": 1631185917
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the language of graph theory, it would be the maximal reachable subgraph or the directed induced subgraph</p>",
        "id": 252608592,
        "sender_full_name": "Péter Ferenczy",
        "timestamp": 1631186528
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So maybe it is the maximal reachable subcategory or the induced subcategory of an object. But as always, there must be a dual - and the name should reflect that. I'd then call the dual of this concept the maximal observable subcategory or the coinduced subcategory</p>",
        "id": 252608820,
        "sender_full_name": "Péter Ferenczy",
        "timestamp": 1631186668
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It sounds to me like you might be reaching for the notion of a co-sieve. A sieve on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a set of maps into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> that is closed under precomposition, i.e., if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g:Y\\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> belongs to a sieve and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f:Z\\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>∘</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g\\circ f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.63889em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> belongs to the sieve as well.</p>\n<p>For a co-sieve, we switch the directions of the arrows, which sounds (close?) to what you're looking for.</p>",
        "id": 252613088,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1631188984
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or perhaps the slice category?</p>",
        "id": 252636782,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1631198247
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Good point! The OP didn't say anything about restricting what goes in, and keeping everything gives the (co)slice.</p>",
